 the nature of language for 400 years has been that language is a more or less deficient medium for expressing our thoughts. Linguistic signs are arbitrary and regulated by convention. 
This view is a decisive component of the general, or rational, grammars arising in the 17 century, whose axiomatic basis is in essential ways taken over by modern linguistics and the Chomskyan project of generative (universal) grammar. We argue that this early modern, Cartesian axiomatics is at the root of a number of theoretical and empirical impasses in current linguistic theory. We develop another, non-rationalist, conception of universal grammar, which is historically inspired by a second, today largely forgotten, universal grammar tradition, the late medieval monistic grammars. These are guided by the leading idea that language is non-hereditary: 
The organization of the linguistic sign is the organization of thought, with both organizations reflecting the structure of the real. The project assembles a group of researcher's currently spearheading the view of language as a generator of human thoughts. We aim to seamlessly merge linguistics and philosophy so as to make steps towards a new field where axiomatic assumptions of a philosophical character are recognized as feeding info theoretical linguistic, typological, and neuron linguistic research, and where such research feeds back into philosophy.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-10-04</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/1291772D-DFCE-493A-AEE7-24F7EEAFE0E9"><gtr:id>1291772D-DFCE-493A-AEE7-24F7EEAFE0E9</gtr:id><gtr:name>AHRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>173586</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Please see the comment made in this same box in my subsequent grant, relating to the Talking Brains exhibition project. The intellectual and scientific basis for this project was laid in the present project, though it materialised only as part of the next one.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2016</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>9E7B2655-71FE-4BED-B83F-7FEC5BCB32F9</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes/><gtr:outcomeId>56c4968b384b39.21283261</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Un-Cartesian linguistics has been the first attempt since Chomsky (1965) to fundamentally re-think the nature of 'Universal Grammar' - i.e. the biological basis of human language. While the classical conception of this enterprise is 'Cartesian' in the sense that it separates language from cognition or 'thought', the present grant has for the first time developed theoretically and empirically the position that grammar can be something completely different from what we thought: an organizational principle of human-specific thought. This basic foundational idea has inspired myriad new research lines and papers, including a new large grant that, for the first time, has explored the significance of language to disturbances of the thought process, in psychiatric populations.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Numerous linguists have taken up these ideas by now, and through the follow-up grant that still live now, they are finding their way into medical and psychiatric practice across different sites in the UK and in Spain, as well as across a network of clinical partners in Europe that has formed to explore these ideas.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>E3D1CE88-83A1-4AC8-868A-1D1A148DDB28</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56c496d09fab71.49453002</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Education,Healthcare</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>B50B6678-03D7-45F0-9A92-5D44955F0BB7</gtr:id><gtr:title>On the absence of X-within-X recursion in human grammar</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Linguistic Inquiry</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/538a76a8f7d5db65a30bf30d6605a264"><gtr:id>538a76a8f7d5db65a30bf30d6605a264</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Hinzen W</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_354403666513a4735c</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>3F9509A3-B192-4588-964B-8862B3A1CA82</g